</li></ul></li></ul></li><li id="tree_64192196" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64192196" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64192196" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64192196" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64192196" name="comment_link_64192196" href="//slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23206524&amp;cid=64192196" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64192196)" >Re:How to lose your best staff</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64192196" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64192196); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Ol+Olsoc">Ol Olsoc</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Ol+Olsoc">( 1175323 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64192196">		
		on Saturday January 27, 2024 @09:58AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23206524&amp;cid=64192196">#64192196</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64192196"><p><div class="quote"><p>The latest studies and studies of studies actually show that there is no measurable difference in productivity between working form home and in an office. This means that there will be little immediate difference in profitability between the two. The improvement from better workers going to Companies that allow working from home will take at least a year or two to become apparent, and most Companies are locked into real estate contracts or own the offices, so any improvement from that will take at least a couple of years to filter through. Come back in 2030 to see the results of these changes.</p></div><p>Can you show me the facts that better workers do not want to go to a workplace and be around other people? </p><p>
There is a running theme in here that refusal to go to a workplace is somehow a mark of the very best and most competent people. Every time I get into a discussion about remote work, people let me know that is what they believe.  </p><p>
Time for y'all to show us the beef. </p><p>

I believe that no, there is very little to no difference in productivity.  And that is because the location the work is done isn't a major factor in the person's ability. </p><p>
And it is more complex than just location. </p><p>
I've had employees that might be good, but they might need what is called intense supervision. They might get distracted, they might procrastinate. Or employees that aren't so good, but they parrot all of the victim narrative. (a problem in the human presence workplace as well) </p><p>

So I find it hard to believe that people that really want to never come into a workplace are soley those of the highest caliber. They are a mixture of temperaments and abilities, just like the rest of us.</p><p>
But there are some issues with the "I only work from home" outlook. </p><p>

One of course, is that you limit your employment opportunities. Not every job is compatible with such an outlook. Many lucrative careers require working in person and around others. </p><p>
Another is it has a certain limit on your advancement options. You are not qualified for any advanced position that requires you to come to work. Is that a problem? Well, is your skillset one that enjoys stasis?</p><p>
There is a huge empathy gap between people that management works with and people they only see on a computer screen. That is related to how rude we are to each other online. The remote employee is just an avatar. To the person in the office, it is like they tell the computer to do something and the computer does it, not an actual human. </p><p>
Contrast that with interacting with people in the office. Unless a person is a true ass, networking and personal interactions bond people together. Once I "discovered" networking, my career took off. And before being called cynical, I discovered that the people I work with are okay. They have traits that engender care by others. </p><p>
Now of course, some programmers are introverted, acerbic or even misanthropic.  But that's an issue for them to work on if they want to get ahead. Introversion isn't a fault as such, but it shouldn't be allowed to control your life - just the same as extroversion. Acerbic needs taught manners, and misanthropy, well good luck with that. </p><p>
Yes, there are some people for whom remote only work is not a bad idea at all. But it comes at a real cost.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64192196">
